The '''A590''' is a [[trunk road]] in southern [[Cumbria]], in the [[North West England|north-west]] of [[England]]. It runs north-east to south-west from [[M6 motorway|M6]] junction 36, through the towns of [[Ulverston]] and [[Barrow-in-Furness]] to terminate at [[Biggar Bank]] on [[Walney Island]].<ref name="sabre">[http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/roadlists/r10/notes.php?number=A590 A590: M6 J36 (Crooklands) - Walney Island] SABRE; Accessed 07-05-08</ref>  The road is a mixture of [[dual carriageway]] and [[single carriageway]], with the section east of [[Low Newton, Cumbria]] to the M6 being mainly dual. Further dual sections are south of [[Newby Bridge]], south of [[Greenodd]] and south of [[Ulverston]]. The road is the main route for tourists entering the southern [[Lake District]].<ref>[http://www.lake-district-peninsulas.co.uk/towns-villages.htm Destinations in Lake District Peninsulas] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509144806/http://www.lake-district-peninsulas.co.uk/towns-villages.htm |date=9 May 2008 }} Lake-district-peninsulas.co.uk; Accessed 07-05-08</ref> It has often humorously been described as "the longest cul-de-sac in the world".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/jan/04/middlesbrough-barrow Barrow boys are brought back to earth] guardian.co.uk; Accessed 05-01-08</ref>

==Route==

===M6 to Ulverston===
[[File:A590(T) - geograph.org.uk - 872779.jpg|thumb|left|A590 by-pass at High and Low Newton]]
From east to west, the A590 originally terminated at the [[A6 road (Great Britain)|A6 road]] near [[Levens, Cumbria|Levens]].<ref name="sabre" /> Its route followed a number of country roads via a series of Turn Off To Stay On [[List of road-related terminology#T|(TOTSO)'s]], passing through a number of villages including [[Lindale, Cumbria|Lindale]], [[High Newton|High]] and [[Low Newton, Cumbria|Low Newton]], [[Newby Bridge]] and [[Greenodd]] into the larger town of [[Ulverston]]. This road formed a large part of the southern boundary of the [[Lake District National Park]] upon its formation in 1951.

This stretch of road has now undergone a series of improvements and route alignments. In the mid-1970s, the [[A591 road|A591]] '[[Kendal]] link road' was built between Junction 36 of the M6 and Kendal <ref>[http://www.route6.co.uk/m6junction36.html M6 Junction 36] Route 6; Accessed 7 May 2008</ref> with an extension of the A590 also being constructed to join this as part of the wider [[Lancashire]] expressways plans.<ref>[https://archive.is/20040123002934/http://www.lmars.co.uk/roads.html ROADS IN LANCASHIRE: Historic Overview and Maps] Lancashire Motorways and Roads Site; Accessed 7 May 2008</ref> This improvement to the A590 also included a realignment and dualling of the road to the west as far as High Newton, by-passing Lindale. In the mid-1990s the A590 was extended eastward through a re-numbering of the A591 between [[Sizergh]] and the M6, providing a single road between Barrow-in-Furness and the M6.<ref name="sabre" />

West of the Lindale bypass is the road's most recent improvement, a 2.4-mile (3.8-kilometre) long stretch of dual carriageway built to bypass High and Low Newton at a cost of [[GBP|£]]35.3 million.<ref>[http://www.a590.co.uk/home.asp Welcome to the A590 Now Campaign - Bypass  realised - traffic flowing!] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515220915/http://www.a590.co.uk/home.asp |date=15 May 2008 }} Accessed 7 May 2008</ref> This new stretch of road was constructed to a high environmental standard and achieved a [[CEEQUAL]] Award following its opening in Spring 2008.<ref>[http://www.ceequal.com/award33.asp CEEQUAL Award - A590 High and Low Newton Bypass] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107024717/http://www.ceequal.com/award33.asp |date=7 January 2009 }}</ref> It connects to the original route to the east of Newby Bridge. The A590 reaches its most northern point at the foot of [[Windermere]], before following the route of the [[River Leven, Cumbria|River Leven]] to its estuary at Greenodd.<ref name="sabre" /> Both the villages of Backbarrow and Greenodd have now been by-passed, though parts of this route remain narrow and winding.<ref name="sabre" /> West of Greenodd the road switches between sections of single and dual carriageway.

===Ulverston-Walney Island===
[[File:Walney Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 1434582.jpg|thumb|left|A590 crossing Walney Bridge in Barrow-in-Furness]]
The A590 passes through Ulverston,<ref name="sabre" /> avoiding its most central streets, along an inner relief road. West of Ulverston the road is entirely single carriageway and is mainly used for commuting between Ulverston, Barrow-in-Furness and the small towns in-between the two.<ref name="sabre" /> West of [[Dalton-in-Furness]], the A590 follows an entirely different route to that it did prior to the early 1990s when Dalton was bypassed. Previously, the road had gone through Dalton and entered Barrow along the wide [[Victorian era|Victorian]] [[Abbey Road, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey Road]], before passing through Barrow's shipyard onto [[Barrow Island, Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Island]].<ref name="sabre" />

Since 1992, the road has followed a modern bypass close to the [[South Lakes Safari Zoo]] and enters Barrow via its north-western industrial area, parallel to [[Walney Island]] passing the site of Barrow's former [[iron]] and [[steel]]works. A [[one-way traffic|one way]] system opened in April 2008 now applies to the road as it passes closest to the centre of Barrow, with westbound traffic heading towards the town centre at [[Craven Park (Barrow)|Craven Park]] roundabout and eastbound traffic continuing through the industrial land alongside Walney Channel.<ref>[http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=830671 How many people will die?]{{dead link|date=September 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} [[North West Evening Mail]] 29 April 2008; Accessed 7 May 2008</ref> The road continues westward over the [[Walney Bridge|Jubilee Bridge]] onto [[Walney Island]] and terminates at the [[Irish Sea]]

