{{short description|Subduction zone off the east coast of New Zealand's North Island}}
The '''Hikurangi Margin''' is an active [[subduction zone]] extending off the east coast of New Zealand's [[North Island]], where the [[Pacific Plate|Pacific]] and [[Australian Plate|Australian plate]]s collide.<ref name="Science Learning Hub" >{{cite web
 |title=Hikurangi Margin
 |publisher=[[The University of Waikato]]
 |url=http://sciencelearn.org.nz/About-this-site/Glossary/Hikurangi-Margin
}}</ref> It is the southern portion of the [[Kermadec-Tonga subduction zone|Tonga–Kermadec–Hikurangi subduction zone]] and its main feature is the [[Hikurangi Trench]].

Earthquakes of up to 8.2M have been recorded on the Hikurangi Margin, generating local tsunamis, and earthquakes in the 9.0M range are thought to be possible.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wallace|first=Laura M.|first2 =Ursula A.|last2=Cochran|date=June 2014|title=Earthquake and Tsunami Potential of the Hikurangi Subduction Thrust, New Zealand: Insights from Paleoseismology, GPS, and Tsunami Modeling|url=http://tos.org/oceanography/article/earthquake-and-tsunami-potential-of-the-hikurangi-subduction-thrust-newzeal|journal=[[Oceanography (journal)|Oceanography]]|volume=27 |issue=2 |pages= |doi=10.5670/oceanog.2014.46 }}</ref> The [[Ruatoria]] debris avalanche originated on the north part of the subduction zone and probably occurred around 170,000 years ago.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Collot |first=John-Yves |title=The giant Ruatoria debris avalanche on the northern Hikurangi margin, New Zealand: Result of oblique seamount subduction|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1029/2001JB900004/full|journal=[[Journal of Geophysical Research: Solid Earth]]|volume=106 |issue=B9 |pages= 19,271-19,297 |date=September 10, 2001 }}</ref>

